label("$A$", pA, SE);
label("$B$", pB, NE);
label("$C$", pC, W);
draw(circle(pO, 1));
[/asy] Since $AO = CO,$ we have that $\triangle AOC$ is isosceles, and so $\angle CAO = \angle ACO = 18^\circ.$ We are given that $AC = BC,$ we can see that $\triangle BOC \cong \triangle AOC,$  so $\angle BCO = 18^\circ.$ Now, $\angle ACB = \angle OAC + \angle BCO = 36^\circ,$ and as $\angle ACB$ is an inscribed angle, we have $\angle AOB = 2 \cdot \angle ACB = \boxed{72^\circ}.$

By the angle bisector theorem, $AC/CD = AB/BD = 105/42 = 5/2$.  Let $AC = 5x$ and $CD = 2x$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.03 cm);

